>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>4 Minute Timer</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Set a precise 4-minute countdown for productivity micro-breaks, Tabata training, or brewing tea.</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Timer Application -->
    <div class="timer-container">
      <div class="timer-display" id="timer-display">04:00</div>
      <div class="timer-progress-bg">
        <div class="timer-progress-bar" id="timer-progress"></div>
      </div>
      <div class="timer-controls">
        <button id="btn-start" class="btn primary">Start</button>
        <button id="btn-pause" class="btn secondary" disabled>Pause</button>
        <button id="btn-reset" class="btn outline">Reset</button>
      </div>
      <audio id="timer-alarm" src="https://assets.mixkit.co/active_storage/sfx/2869/2869-preview.mp3" preload="auto"></audio>
    </div>

    <script is:inline>
      document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
        const display = document.getElementById('timer-display');
        const progressBar = document.getElementById('timer-progress');
        const btnStart = document.getElementById('btn-start');
        const btnPause = document.getElementById('btn-pause');
        const btnReset = document.getElementById('btn-reset');
        const alarm = document.getElementById('timer-alarm');

        const TOTAL_SECONDS = 4 * 60;
        let remainingSeconds = TOTAL_SECONDS;
        let isRunning = false;
        let endTime = null;
        let timerInterval = null;

        function updateDisplay() {
          const m = Math.floor(remainingSeconds / 60);
          const s = Math.floor(remainingSeconds % 60);
          display.textContent = `${m.toString().padStart(2, '0')}:${s.toString().padStart(2, '0')}`;

          const percentage = ((TOTAL_SECONDS - remainingSeconds) / TOTAL_SECONDS) * 100;
          progressBar.style.width = `${percentage}%`;

          if (remainingSeconds <= 10 && remainingSeconds > 0) {
            display.style.color = '#ef4444'; // Red warning
          } else if (remainingSeconds === 0) {
            display.style.color = '#22c55e'; // Green complete
          } else {
            display.style.color = ''; // Reset
          }
        }

        function tick() {
          if (!isRunning) return;

          const now = Date.now();
          remainingSeconds = Math.max(0, (endTime - now) / 1000);

          updateDisplay();

          if (remainingSeconds <= 0) {
            clearInterval(timerInterval);
            isRunning = false;
            btnStart.disabled = false;
            btnPause.disabled = true;
            btnStart.textContent = "Start";

            // Play alarm
            alarm.currentTime = 0;
            alarm.play().catch(e => console.log("Audio play prevented by browser policy", e));

            // Notification if allowed
            if (Notification.permission === "granted") {
              new Notification("Timer Complete", { body: "Your 4-minute timer is up!" });
            }
          }
        }

        btnStart.addEventListener('click', () => {
          if (remainingSeconds <= 0) return;

          // Request notification permission on first interaction
          if (Notification.permission === "default") {
            Notification.requestPermission();
          }

          isRunning = true;
          endTime = Date.now() + (remainingSeconds * 1000);
          timerInterval = setInterval(tick, 50); // High frequency for smooth progress bar

          btnStart.disabled = true;
          btnPause.disabled = false;
        });

        btnPause.addEventListener('click', () => {
          isRunning = false;
          clearInterval(timerInterval);

          btnStart.disabled = false;
          btnPause.disabled = true;
          btnStart.textContent = "Resume";
        });

        btnReset.addEventListener('click', () => {
          isRunning = false;
          clearInterval(timerInterval);
          remainingSeconds = TOTAL_SECONDS;

          btnStart.disabled = false;
          btnPause.disabled = true;
          btnStart.textContent = "Start";

          alarm.pause();
          alarm.currentTime = 0;

          updateDisplay();
        });

        // Initialize display
        updateDisplay();
      });
    </script>

    <section class="content-body">
      <h2>The Psychology of the 4 Minute Micro-Break</h2>
      <p>When implementing productivity frameworks like the Pomodoro technique, conventional wisdom dictates working for 25 minutes followed by a 5-minute break. However, many developers, writers, and highly focused professionals are migrating toward the <strong>4 minute timer</strong> instead. Why shave exactly 60 seconds off the standard rest period?</p>

      <p>The answer lies in the psychology of "context switching." When you take a full 5-minute break, there is enough time to completely disengage from your current task. You might open a new browser tab, start scrolling social media, or get invested in a different problem entirely. By limiting the break to precisely 4 minutes, you allow your eyes to rest and your brain to reset, but the duration is just short enough that your working memory remains loaded with your current coding problem or writing task.</p>

      <h2>Practical Applications of a 4 Minute Timer</h2>
      <p>Beyond productivity micro-breaks, a 240-second countdown is an incredibly common duration for various daily tasks. The specific temporal length makes it a uniquely versatile tool.</p>

      <h3>Tabata Interval Training</h3>
      <p>In the world of fitness, Tabata is a highly specific form of High-Intensity Interval Training (HIIT). Developed by Dr. Izumi Tabata, the protocol is notoriously brutal but highly efficient: 20 seconds of maximum effort exercise, followed by 10 seconds of rest, repeated 8 times. The entire routine takes exactly 4 minutes. A dedicated <strong>4 minute timer</strong> is essential here, as the short rest periods make it impossible to manually track the time on a standard clock.</p>

      <h3>Culinary Precision</h3>
      <p>In the kitchen, 4 minutes is the golden number for several crucial recipes. For instance, creating the perfect soft-boiled egg—where the whites are fully set but the yolk remains a warm, runny liquid—requires boiling exactly 4 minutes. Similarly, brewing delicate green or white teas for more than 4 minutes extracts excessive tannins, resulting in a bitter cup. Precision timing is the difference between perfection and ruin.</p>

      <div class="callout">
        <h3>The Math Behind the Timer</h3>
        <p>Building a robust timer in JavaScript requires understanding how the browser handles background tabs. If you simply use <code>setInterval</code> to subtract one second every 1000 milliseconds, your timer will fall behind when you switch tabs, as modern browsers throttle background script execution to save battery.</p>
        <p>Our timer avoids this by using absolute timestamps via <code>Date.now()</code>. When you click start, it calculates the exact future end time. Every "tick," it compares the current real-world time to the end time, ensuring 100% accuracy regardless of browser throttling.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Why It Matters: Reclaiming Intentional Time</h2>
      <p>In a digital environment designed to steal your attention, using a strict, short timer forces intentionality. When you know you only have 4 minutes, you don't casually start watching a YouTube video; you stand up, stretch, get a glass of water, and return to your desk. It turns passive procrastination into an active, structured recovery period.</p>

      <p>Whether you are using this <strong>4 minute timer</strong> to execute a grueling Tabata workout, brew a flawless cup of tea, or optimize your deep work sessions, tracking your time with precision is the first step toward mastering it. The brevity of the countdown is its greatest strength, serving as a rapid reset button for your brain and body.</p>

      <div class="card">
        <h3>Explore More Tools</h3>
        <p>If you're interested in other timer tools, check out our <a href="/pomodoro-timer">Pomodoro Timer</a> for structured focus sessions, or explore our <a href="/best-timer-apps">Best Timer Apps</a> guide to find the perfect productivity tool.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What can I use a 4 minute timer for?</summary>
        <p>A 4 minute timer is ideal for productivity micro-breaks, brewing a perfect cup of green tea, performing Tabata high-intensity interval training, or boiling soft-boiled eggs.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why is a 4 minute micro-break better than a 5 minute one?</summary>
        <p>The 4-minute interval is psychologically beneficial because it feels distinctly shorter than a 5-minute block. It prevents the brain from fully disengaging from the task at hand, minimizing context-switching penalties when you resume work.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How does Tabata training use 4 minutes?</summary>
        <p>Tabata is a form of HIIT that lasts exactly 4 minutes. It consists of 8 rounds of 20 seconds of intense exercise followed by 10 seconds of rest. A dedicated 4 minute timer is essential for tracking this brief but intense protocol.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Will this 4 minute timer run in the background?</summary>
        <p>Yes, our web-based timer utilizes absolute time tracking via JavaScript's Date.now(), meaning it will continue to count down accurately even if you switch tabs or minimize the browser window.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How many seconds are in 4 minutes?</summary>
        <p>There are exactly 240 seconds in 4 minutes. (4 minutes × 60 seconds = 240 seconds).</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>

